<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05156j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05156j">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05156j"> 156(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> sphere = fair / race = Lucrece / sea = say</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Dr. Joyce points out that the correct English sound of the diphthongs <i>ea</i> and <i>ei</i> and of long e, was the same as long a in &ldquo;fate&rdquo; from Elizabethan to comparatively recent times. Thus Cowper rhymes &ldquo;sea&rdquo; with &ldquo;way&rdquo;; Tate and Brady rhyme &ldquo;conceive&rdquo; with &ldquo;grave&rdquo;; while Pope rhymes &ldquo;race&rdquo; with &ldquo;Lucrece&rdquo; and &ldquo;sphere&rdquo; with &ldquo;fair.&rdquo; <small> Alfred Perceval Graves, <a name="ILMS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ILMS"><cite title="source">Irish Literary and Musical Studies</cite></a>, (1913) [The English Spoken in Ireland] 17</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
